< Review>
Hands down the best restaurant in San Francisco ! The Chef is a god with food and the bartender is incredible.  The service was exceptional.  Elegance and romantic atmosphere, minus the live karaoke guy in the corner.
Will definitely be back and recommend this place to all.</Review>

<Rating>3< /Rating>< Text>
Steaks and drinks excellent. Service on point. Management was aloof and not as professional as the experienced staff. The bartender was rude to my date, post meal which left us walking away sad. We spent over 500 dollars for the two of us, including 15 for every side of butter not included with the meal. Lobster mashed potatoes are soupy. I commented to the manager who insisted they are supposed to be soupy. He also made it clear he's afraid to criticize the chef. I've been in the industry for almost 30 years. Auto-gratuity hurts the staff. Just being honest.<//Text>

< Text>
Celebrated my birthday here. Sat in the rooftop semi-outdoor space. It was a bit cool as the skin went down, but still a comfortable experience. We started with cocktails (good), crab cocktail appetizer (ok. Seemed previously frozen) and the bone-in filet, bone-in ribeye, sauteed broccoli, and lobster mac and cheese. Overall tasty meal. They surprised me with a complimentary slice of cheesecake beautifully decorated. We also ordered the butter cake which was amazing. We will certainly be back!</Text>

<rate>5</rate><user>101976289475634415008<//user><date>1583417026161< /date><name>Garret J</name><Pictures>None</Pictures><Response>None</Response><gmap_id>0x808581e76ab80ee9:0x20d6791cd5ff982a</gmap_id><Text>Glad they finally opened in SF.  As good as their other locations.</Text></record></dataset><record>
<Pictures>None<//Pictures><Gmap_id>0x808581e76ab80ee9:0x20d6791cd5ff982a</Gmap_id>< text>
My Star Scale:
1 Star = Do not recommend
2 Star = Do not recommend but there were      positive aspects of the experience.
3 Star = Would recommend
4 Star = Would recommend ++service OR ++ food OR ++ ambiance (2 of 3)
5 Star = Would recommend ++service AND ++ food AND ++ambiance (3 of 3)

So the new Mastro's in SF is all about the hype and they definitely come though. Rediculous ambiance and service to back up the food, you are definitely getting your money's worth at this awesome high end steak and seafood restaurant. I've been to other Mastro's locations and this one ranks highly amongst the chain.  The attention to detail and food execution was impressive. Gluten free items are in abundance here and since they serve a la carte, ordering gluten free couldn't be easier!  By design, appetizers and side dishes are meant to be served family style. We went with lobster mashed potatoes, brussel sprouts, and steamed spinach. All awesome choices and very complementary to the main dishes we all chose.   Mastro's is known for their steaks right?  So I ordered up a Kansas City strip (basically a bone in NY strip). Bone in, changed the entire flavor profile of the strip for me and took it to an entirely different level. They asked how I would like it cooked and they hit it exactly as I asked for, medium with red in the center (a true medium).  Mastro's also serves A5 wagyu at up to $300 bucks a cut, but I know what I can appreciate and the strip I ordered was absolutely delicious.  We didn't order seafood during this visit but I've had the signature seafood tower here before and if you are up for awesome chilled lobster, crab, oysters, shrimp etc, this is a must have.  We corked our our own wine but the wine selection is never ending here, and they have a great selection at various price points to fit what you are looking for. Very attentive wait service but not overwhelming at the same time.  5 Star for sure.  If your are looking for high end quality food, awesome service and fantastic ambiance then this is the spot to go to. You don't just stumble across Mastro's SF, you plan on going there....< /text>

< review>
I will highly recommend this place to anyone looking for a really nice upscale dinner without getting a coursed meal.
There is a strict upscale dress code.
Making reservations its ez by phone or online.
The cork fee is 40 dollars for a 750mil bottle.
We opted to bring our bottle of Dom perignon witch if purchased on side will run you for $300
So I payed $170 for my bottle plus $40 cork fee and saved me a few  bucks.
Prices are to be expected high, and average tap for 2 with a few cocktails a few appetisers 2 antrees and dessert will run at about  $300+.
We had 2 appetisers, 2 cocktails, 2 antrees, 2 side dishes and a dessert.
Our bill was 375$
Here is a list of dishes ordered.
Roasted bone marrow.
Seafood tower.
South of France cocktail.
Elder flower martini.
Filet 8oz.
Bone-In Filet 12oz.
Alaskan King Crab Black Truffle Gnocchi.
Rosemary Garlic SauteÃÅed Mushrooms.
Butter Cake.
The Bone marrow is really good an will recomend it to anyone willing to try something new. How ever the one we got was a bit gamey. I have to say I had better but I would still recommend it.
please note that the seafood tower is fully customisable and they will plated on a tower with dri ice on it witch make it really cool and hazy I recommend if your trying to impress your special someone or if you just love sea food we got shrimp cocktail which is 3 jumbo size shrimp they are extremely fresh and succulent also got 2 king crab claws that I would not recommend getting due to their small size your better of getting the king crab legs.
The 2 cocktail we got were really good and would recommend trying them out.
The filets were good but I wish I actually had ordered the Bone in ribeye.
The side dishes were delicious and huge they come on a big hot saute pan which completely kill the hole upscale dinner experience in my opinion.
I mean here we are sitting with this really nice dinner on a beautiful set table and the they bring out two big saut√© pans and leave them there on the middle on the table personally I would recommend the sides to be plated on a nice side dish patle or some kind of small cast iron plate but that's just me.
Over all our experience here was amazing and the food was great along with really nice and friendly staff and professionall service.</review>

< review>
If you‚Äôre looking for a fantastic steakhouse with quality steak, amazing service, great ambience and satisfaction for the premium price, KEEP LOOKING.... Most overrated restaurant and dining experience in SF. I had high hopes for Mastro‚Äôs. They have some serious kinks to work out in this restaurant. I have never waited so long (nearly an hour) for a table when a reservation was booked in advance. It took 30 minutes to get drinks after we put our order in at the bar while waiting. By the time we got seated and our orders came, we literally spent 3.5 hours in this place and we were only 2 people. And the most peculiar thing is apparently the VIP bread basket is the most exclusive item on their menu. It literally took 30 minutes before we finally got a bread basket, despite my multiple check-ins.

Management has not spent enough time educating their staff on the menu or the wine list.

The ambience was almost like walking into the set of a ghetto music video. Why is the music so loud and obnoxious? Why does the decor look like a high end brothel? For such an expensive restaurant, this place has ZERO CLASS and poor ambiance.

The only positives here were our table server had a lovely personality. Unfortunately, poor management and operational inefficiencies make her job very hard.

Food wise, I don‚Äôt find the product worth the price. I ordered a fillet medium rare. It was ok at best. It was dry, had no tenderness, and was over-salted. The Brussel sprouts tasted like the grass growing in my backyard with some salt poured over it. There was so much cream in the mashed potatoes, I thought I had drank an entire gravy boat after two bites.

Drink wise, if you‚Äôre going to charge $20+ for a cocktail on the rocks, use a single clear ice cube. That is standard at most cocktail bars when ordering an old fashioned or similar cocktail. Mastro‚Äôs used the same ice in the cocktails as their water glasses.

Additionally, the design is poorly done. For a massive two story restaurant, there should be a bathroom available on each level. Also, at this price point there should be valet parking.

Every steakhouse in SF is better than this one, including your own house with a cut of grocery chain store meat on the grill.

Save your time and  money. Go elsewhere.</review>

Using the body scan method they can pinpoint where things are out of alignment and make the necessary corrections with the Activator which makes micro adjustments or they can do a good old fashioned manual adjustment. I usually opt for the Activator, unless I feel the need for a little more and go with a manual or drop table. All the massage therapist are good and have their own unique style. Beau has recently started taping my back which has surprisingly helped. Shanon has a one of a kind massage technique that completely relaxes your body and her hour massage is well worth the price. So there are a lot of options to get your body working and feeling better.lo</text>

<user_name>James Rodda< /user_name><Date>1605596363443< /Date>< rating>
4<//rating>
<Text>It is now my senior year at John Adams, and I would highly recommend putting your children here if they wish to learn. Most of those who posted a bad review did so because of their lack of willingness to learn and to do their work. It is a tough school, and there is lots of reading and annotating of primary sources but the main reason that it is a good school is because the teachers and curriculum are there to get you to think. The books I have read and the discussions I have had in class are far more advanced then anything my friends at other public schools are reading. In order to get the best grades, you have to be able to show that you can think, not just that you can memorize. As with any school there are minor problems, but the drama level is surprisingly low, and the people are quite friendly. It is a good choice of school: the people who have the best experiences here are the ones who are willing to learn, and do their work.< /Text>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

<UserId.>102623135370408395060< /UserId.><Name>Christian M<//Name>< time>
1591308845506<//time>
<Rate>4<//Rate><Review>Student since the first year here! I have attended the school since fourth grade. I am now a Senior. I can honestly say that I love this school. The teachers are amazing (with a few exceptions, as with any school). They are honestly great people and take the time to get to know you personally. They will stop and ask how you are doing in the halls, make sure you don't need help on homework, and genuinely want to learn from the scholars as well as teach. The staff is friendly and helpful, and most of the scholars are nice and studious (we don't have bullying problems or much swearing because the majority of scholars are religious [LDS and Catholic are the two big ones]) Sadly, the administration is not as good, having a tendency toward unpreparedness and inconsistency. This is probably not the school for you if you don't enjoy a rigorous education. There are often philosophical discussions, debates, and socratic discussions, even in classes such as math and science. We don't have a great sports program unfortunately. However,  we have great music and art program and plenty of things to do if you are interested in debate, philosophy and a classic education. I highly recommend checking out the library.<//Review><pics>None</pics>< Response>

< Review>
My car was overheating due to a failing thermostat so I brought it to AAMCO for the repairs. I felt that they were stalling on the diagnosis (4 days) so I did some research on my own and found that this was a very labor intensive repair for my specific vehicle (around 8 hrs). After the diagnosis I was told that they wouldn't be able to begin the repairs for a couple of days. I ended up taking the car to another shop who diagnosed and completed the repairs within two days (thank you Roseville Volkswagen). During this time I was in a rental car provided through my extended warranty with a time limit of five days, so getting the repairs done in a timely manner would have saved me from having to pay out of pocket for the rental. The reason I was dissatisfied was the lack of communication/directness. Yes, 8 hours to change a thermostat is probably not the most economical use of time for your techs. However, I would have greatly appreciated being advised to take my vehicle elsewhere in the interest of getting the repairs done in a timely manner. In fairness, the staff were friendly and knowledgeable but I will not be taking any of my vehicles here again.<//Review>

< text>
We took our GMC in as we noticed what appeared to be transmission fluid on the driveway under the vehicle... and Aamco were suppose to be the transmission experts. They called to tell us the vehicle was fixed and that they were taking it on a final test drive to ensure all was working well.  Other than the length of time it took, at this point I was happy they found issue and got it fixed.  Next call, which we got was on our way over to the shop to pick up the vehicle, they told us that the transmission blew on the test drive.  I was thinking, well we brought them a running vehicle, they told us transmission was fine, and the transmission blew after their work on their test drive, so OF COURSE they would make it right and give us back a running vehicle.  But NO, they wanted thousands to rebuild our transmission.  The best they would offer was to give us a credit of the $300 toward the cost to rebuild transmission.  Um, not sure about you, but at this point I had lost all confidence in this establishment both as a repair facility and as a business that does the right thing or that takes care of their customers.  Since it was evident they weren't going to do the right thing, we just wanted vehicle back to take it to someone else for repairs, but they refused to release vehicle without us paying them the $300 (for blowing the transmission..really?)  Then it got even worse when they wanted us to come and get it or they would start charging us storage fees.  Really???  This is NOT how to run a business.  I understand things break, but the ones that break them should be responsible for fixing them, a moral that this business doesn't get.  We took vehicle to dealership in the end to get a new transmission and it runs great now.  But still  not happy that this little experience with Aamco cost us nearly $4,000.  I would NEVER take another vehicle to them.  If i want a vehicle destroyed, I would just send it over a cliff, much faster and cheaper, and a ton less aggravation.</text>

<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
This is the last place I visited before leaving state and it was a great send-off to say the least.
Every time I came to this spot, I was always greeted with a chill vibe and many vegan treats to scour and eventually, devour. The donuts are lit simply put and the soy lattes go hard here. I just love that this place is basically a vegan haven for you veg refugees out there looking for a solid and pretty affordable place. If you want a stable charge but not a jittery caffeine experience, the coffee does that with finesse here.
I remember many Gilman mornings with an east bay express in hand, coming here for those killer dairy free lattes. Topped off with a ciggy, you've got yourself the made in the bay.< /text>

< Rate>

< text>
My go-to cafe. The lavender latte is phenomenal, especially cold, as is the clove latte or cardamom latte. The best thing about the cafe, though, is their mexican hot chocolate - rich, spicy, and not too sweet. If you don't like overly sweet drinks, this places makes it da bomb. As someone who can't have dairy, I also appreciate that they don't charge extra for non-vegan drinks.

I've been here at various times and the quality of the drinks does vary by the barista. If you want quality drinks, go on a weekday afternoon - there's a barista with a pixie cut on Wednesdays, for instance (sorry, I don't know your name!) and her drinks are 1000% better than the others.< /text>

<review>TL;DR: good coffee, nice pastries, but there's that one rude barista who doesn't understand how to be a good neighbor to the other businesses on the street or how to be considerate of the customer's needs. A real shame.

PROS: very nice coffee, knowledgeable baristas. I'm not much of a pastry eater, but the couple of times I've tried one, it was quite good- especially the Yam Rolls. Most of the baristas are very cool people.

CONS: just the one, really, but it's kinda pissing me off. So, I've been a semi-regular at this cafe for a few months, went there maybe twice a week. I work online in cafes, and I make a point of buying a couple drinks each time and tip to contribute. I never had anyone at this shop give me a sense that I'd overstayed my welcome. They claimed to not have a bathroom, and told me I should walk down the street to the market. Since I don't feel right using a business's bathroom without buying something, and since Coffee Conscious only has pastries to eat anyways, I'd generally pick up lunch. Suddenly today, I was told not to eat outside food in the shop.

I was a barista for years, and I get that this is generally a no-no. But being that they were sending people to another business to use the bathroom, I figured it was reasonable to grab something. In the course of the conversation about this, the barista said something about the shop being small, basically implying that they're not cool with "campers." Fine, I get that too. But here's the thing- there was NOBODY else sitting when I arrived, and the cafe wasn't full in the whole time I was there. Also, there are some regulars who come in every day and take up basically half of the place. I like regulars, and I like supporting local businesses. But when they're all but throwing folks out on the one hand, and shmoozing others who are going to stay just as long on the other hand, it seems a little hypocritical.

Also hypocritical- they DO have a bathroom, and I've seen friends of the baristas using it. They've got to set the rules, I understand that, but when they make people needing a bathroom another business's problem (and BTW, it's a medical issue for some), it's not right for them to also complain about you supporting that business. And if you want to keep people moving through, don't selectively enforce that. Support local businesses- all of them. I'll be at Royal Ground on Solano.</review><Gmap_id>0x80857ec9caf33e17:0x3de8bd771a1d44c< /Gmap_id>< username>
Daniel Elkan<//username>

We got to the hotel next door late and found out that the power was out. We had not prepared to pay with cash and were all hungry.

After scrounging together everything we had, we were like twenty cents short. The woman seeking the counter said something like "no problem, we're all in this together."

Seriously, where do you find such amazing service and people these days? I will definitely babe a point to return to Parkside Pizza next time I'm in town.

<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
The best pizza I've tasted in my life in 2013.

I stayed at the lodge nearby with a Groupon and after a short hike we bussed back. It was a chilly December evening when we walked in for a Pizza and submitted our orders.

It was so delicious that it was unbelievable. All four of us were confused at something so good. We attributed it to the hike but ordered another pizza to test our theory. It was just as delicious despite our stomach's bursting.

We ate there every evening for the remainder of our two night stay. I write this review because I had the hardest time finding "Pizza place in Yosemite" and now that I finally found it I can look back on this review for my next visit to Yosemite.< /text>

<UserId.>109290458429053691913</UserId.>< name>

< time>
1563666658118< /time>
< Rating>
4</Rating>
< Text>
The pizza and the service were great at this little pizza place just outside of the entrance to Yosemite. We stayed at the Blue Butterfly Inn tucked away on the river behind the property of the more expansive lodge. Nice to have the option of bringing pizza back to the Inn to eat or eat at Parkside, which we did. It's pretty unassuming, which we liked: you stand in line to order a pizza, find a table to sit at, and they bring it to you. The line was long, but the pizza came out quickly, and the service is attentive and friendly - well worth waiting in line! The crust was cooked just right and the ingredients were fresh and tasty. Eat outside, if you can - the weather on the evening we were there was heavenly. The inside has several tables in it, but the atmosphere outside is much better.<//Text>

<user_id>107444333383263433673< /user_id><Name>Jacqueline Telljohann< /Name><Time>1571876311962< /Time>< rate>
3< /rate>
< review>
Yosemite could really use some decent food options. There's really nothing good in the area.

This looked to have the best Yelp reviews I could find so we came here the first night.

We got a large pizza, half chicken alfredo and half chicken cordon blue. On the positive side, the crust was way better than I expected. I really enjoyed it. The pizza itself was dry though. I couldn't taste any sauce and you would think alfredo and ranch would be noticable flavors. I did like the chicken cordon blue slightly more.

A large was plenty for two people. We ended up not eating it all since we didn't really like it.

We found a sandwich shop in Yosemite Valley (Degnans Kitchen) with free wifi that was better, so we didn't come back here.<//review>

Pro: Nice beer and liquor combos, food is great.

Con: The folks at Zeitgeist seem to be under the impression that COVID-restrictions are a free pass to be massively rude to patrons, even when the "transgressions" have nothing to do with social distancing or ensuring that the area is safe for all. My wife and I were seated before our friend arrived. When he arrived a few minutes later, there was no one at the entrance to show his ID, so he saw us and walked backed to meet us.

Then in a move that was as bizarre as it was rude, the manager/host came over and berated me and my wife for not following his specific instructions to tell.my friend that he had to show his ID before he came back to meet us. Now apart from the fact that my friend immediately produced his ID, and that it is not the responsibility of the patrons to hunt down staff to show their ID, and that the entire situation could have easily been resolved without him being massively rude to us, it was just awkward. We are all adults, and to belittled by some guy because we did not follow his explicit instructions on how my friend should do his job was just odd.

So in closing... go to Standard Deviant on 14th street. Not as many seats, but at the very least you don't get belittled my and dude who looks like a scruffy Jeff Goldblum .< /text>

Very sad to see what this place has become. Maybe they got new managent and I hope they will fix it.

We talked with some of our table neighbors and they were all pretty disappointed..< /text>

<rate>4< /rate><text>Great beer selection. Good grub. Fries and burgers and wings on par / slightly above average< /text><user>103668650491919282663</user><resp>None</resp><Time>1562452928039<//Time>< Pics>

<Gmap_id>0x808f7e20423dcf53:0x95306ba1a91f0acd<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<Response>None<//Response>< text>
Awesome cash-only beer bar. The beer selection is great and the prices are reasonable compared to most places in SF. When you go, know a few things:

1. The bartenders aren't going to wait for you to decide. When you get to the bar, know what you're going to order
2. You're not going to hear top-40 hits here. They play metal. And it's awesome
3. There's a great outdoor seating area but bring a jacket since it can get kinda chilly at night
4. Always tip the bar tenders. They work hard

It's a great spot in SF - enjoy!</text>

< Review>
Zeitgeist philosophy: do what(ever) you want. Just don't let YOUR party off leash. As soon as your party starts partying on others' party, that's the moment that you become a liability and get kicked out. And let's be honest, who HASN'T gotten kicked out of Zeitgeist, anyway?

Haters always gonna hate, but real crew gonna appreciate. Zeitgeist gets ALL THE STARS. Now be good, y'all.<//Review>

<name>Andre Perry</name><time>1560723705416< /time><rate>5< /rate>< review>
One of the best bars in America. No question. Generally rough around the edges but also on the forefront of excellent beer selection. The kitchen hours are at the whim of the cooks' attitude but when it's on they deliver every time. Perhaps best regarded for its expansive beer garden in the middle of a busy city. The most striking aspect of this place is its fierce democratization of its clientele. There are no class-based perks and everyone is equally welcome. A remarkable feat for a town that reflects economic inequality more so than most other  American cities.<//review>

< review>
I really enjoyed the scene here. It's a hip dive bar without the creepers. I loved being able to sit outside and the fact that it was private. The bike rack is cool too for those who bike. The bathrooms were very clean which is a huge plus in my book. I also enjoyed staring at the elephants painted on the wall in the garden.

The bar has a wonderful selection of beer and some ciders. I am not a beer person so I had a cider. Pretty sure it was Blizzard or something like that. It was recommended by the bartender.

I would definitely come here again and recommend it.<//review>

< review>
Outdoor beer garden in the mission that has a lot of seating, and is sheltered from the wind. One of the few outdoor spots in SF that's not that cold! Large beer selection. Limited selection of bar food.

The service is not very friendly. Lots of seating, but can be hard to find a place to sit unless you get there early. I think there's a separate smoking section, but maybe not enforced, so it can be a little smoky. Communal picnic tables, clientele is hit or miss, sometimes friendly and sometimes douchey.<//review>

<UserId.>113794225192714873861<//UserId.>< username>
Nathan Cobb< /username>
<time>1499314251809</time>< Rate>
1<//Rate>
< Review>
I would heavily recommend avoiding this place.
I drove from Chico CA with my girlfriend and her friends to Zeitgeist Bar. She had told us that this place was a great bar with a wonderful patio and pool table.
We walked in and I went to the bathroom.
I came out and met my girlfriend and friends at the door.
We were met by the doorman, (remember, I just walked from the bathroom to the door) and the group was being yelled at by the doorman with a simple, repetitive, statement; "No, get the f*** out"
I asked him what happened and was met with him and another male forcefully, and unexpectedly, shoving me out the door on to the street. I hadn't had a single drink and was given no explanation.
(I feel that I should mention that my back is not in the best shape unfortunately)
I spoke with my girlfriend and her friends and was informed that they had left to look for me since they weren't sure if I had walked outside. Apparently, if you leave the bar at all or are associated with anyone leaving the bar, you are no longer welcome.
We ended up walking to the Crafty Fox just down the street and explained the situation. We were told by the bar tender that it's extremely common to try and keep up their reputation.
What a way to run a bar in San Francisco.
In conclusion, save your money and go somewhere else like we did.
We enjoyed some steak and Mac and made positive memories instead :)< /Review>

< Text>
Grungy rock bar with plenty of atmosphere. Staff were great and very friendly, though you could tell they didn't take you too seriously if you don't look hard enough for them (you shouldn't judge by looks, lets just say I've lived plenty!). Great burgers, juicy and full of flavor. I would have preferred some crispy fries to the lumpy, tater-totesque potatoes offered but no big deal. Was walking from Hayes Valley trying to get to a bar and got caught by a red light. I noticed a skull on the door and thought why not? I was pretty surprised because even though it looked a bit like a dive from the outside -- and is CASH ONLY -- it has a really good selection of beers and is not at all a dive. Zeitgeist is a surly joint full of yuppies in punk clothes, cigarette smoke, and suspicious bartenders.  Patrons glare at you.  You glare back.  Sound fun?

< Review>
This is a great place to go chill with some friends on a sunny day. It's festive with great beer and the way the outdoor section is configured, there's no wind so if they sun is out, it feel pretty warm. You can end up spending a ton of time there. My first year in SF, I held my birthday gathering here. There were tons of room for everyone to hangout and have a blast. Great for people watching and meeting!

The one thing about this place that makes me not want to be a super fan is the fact that I can't eat anything here. I don't eat beef or pork and I hear they have an amazing burger.< /Review>

<user_name>Elias Chedid</user_name>< Time>
1618170469613</Time>
< Rating>
1< /Rating>
<review>Pandemic update: This bar that used to be my headquarters (I had been going there 3 times a week for 3 years before COVID hit) is now the shadow of its former self.
The reasons we would go there were:
-Broad choice of beers on tap (50+)
-Quick service, if you're thirsty you go to the bar and the waiters were the quickest of the West
-Allowed smoking, not many bars with outdoors allow that, Zeitgeist was famous for this
-Opened late, usually midnight on week days and 2AM on weekends

It was the best "dive" bar I had been to and it will always hold a special place in my heart.
Now if you go there:
-Very few beers on tap, no more pitchers!
-You have to wait for the waiters who take forever to notice you to take your order
-You are not allowed to smoke, not even vaping, despite being outdoors and socially distanced from other tables
-They close at 9PM

Some of those changes I can get due to COVID, some others are just this place losing its soul. Good luck and farewell<//review><Pictures>None< /Pictures><resp>None</resp>< Gmap_id>
0x808f7e20423dcf53:0x95306ba1a91f0acd<//Gmap_id>

< username>
Gabriel DeRita< /username>
<Text>One of my favorite bars in San Francisco. Amazing patio where anything goes (no photos please) incredible beer selection, pool table, and generally good crowd. Can get hectic on sunny Saturdays, but its always a good time. The picnic table seating usually facilitates some interesting conversation between groups of strangers, and I've made more new friends at this bar because of it than anywhere else in SF. And its cheap! Word to the wise- don't order food after 10PM. The cook has been there a long, long time, and he doesn't want to make your drunk ass a grilled cheese. Wait for the tamale lady to show up!< /Text></record>

<user>116580660117641009909< /user><username>Steve Wagner</username><date>1376517699966</date><rating>4</rating><Text>Recommended to us as a "more divey" sort of bar with a good beer selection by one of the pour-over baristas at Four Barrel...and well, he couldn't have been more right. Lots of excellent beer on tap (we had the Moonlight Death and Taxes), a large outdoor beer garden, good music, and a skull-bunny on the door. All good.

The only downside? The outdoor beer garden hung under a steady pall of cigarette (and other) smoke, which made it hard for us to hang around for more than a single pint.

In many ways, a grittier, grungier version of the Ginger Man.< /Text><pictures>None</pictures>< Response>

Picnic tables?
Heavy Metal?
Beer?
Kids, welcome to hipster summer camp.
Zeitgeist is hands down the best beer bar in the mission . It has loads of local brews and even some awesome ones straight from belgium. The bloody marys are also perfection.
The atmosphere outside is so fun. If you have a cigarette to spare you will make friends immediately.

You can't have everything.</review>

103379264202553362035< /userid>
< user_name>
Johnny Wang< /user_name>
< Date>
1465165254690</Date>
< Rating>
3< /Rating>
<Text>Came here on a team outing (a.k.a. day drinking) last week, where the lot of us proceeded to polish off a few pitchers of beer over the next few hours, while I was feeling rebellious and chose to nurse my double of rye instead.

While the drinks are pretty standard - don't expect any fancy cocktails here, a la Rickhouse or Zero Zero - the space is pretty neat. There's the usual indoor part of a dive bar, with the pool table and video games, and there's this nice outdoor patio area, replete with picnic tables and benches.

Unfortunately, not so much to my tastes, mostly due to me being more of the cocktail bar/lounge type, but partly since, not only was it too cold to be out in an area lacking heat lamps, but also because the patio was filled with smokers. But hey, if these don't bug you, or you're into the dive scene, Zeitgeist is probably worth checking out.

***Accessibility Info***

Venue - While the front door has a single step that's easy to get up with some help, they also do have an accessible side entrance. Once inside, you have to deal with your usual bar height counters, but they have ramps elsewhere to get you in and out of the patio, should you so choose.

Bathroom - Accessible!</Text><Pics>None<//Pics><Resp>None<//Resp><GmapID>0x808f7e20423dcf53:0x95306ba1a91f0acd</GmapID></record></dataset><record>

After being hassled in the toilets for turning down a request for oral sex from a heavy set, blue haired individual, we were again hassled at the bar for "wrong opinions" (can't remember the exact phrase that was used).

<user>109815267831202318650</user><name>Walter Macalma< /name><time>1449535726684< /time>< Rate>
3<//Rate>
< Text>
Zeitgeist is a dive bar, but unlike most dive bars you've been to or will go to if you get around this place has very little appeal. A good selection of beer and only double tall drinks are what's what though. The pricing is really geared towards beer, the first sign of a dive bar. Second sign is the 1 and only pool table is trashed and supported on boards that could totally break with more than 6 on a board. Definitely creekage. Small groups of mixed groups buddle around corners like a college bar. No bums or degenerates roaming around, no biker's posted up, HH was not to be seen. Prices on the wall were odd, order and then find out. I like the patio, the lounging gardens and that's what saved this place for me.

To me "dive" is an endearing term of feeling free and doing what you want, no judgment from the other patrons, cheap drinks, but when you have clique's and unfriendly people, a thrashed location, a kitchen (dive bars may only have a stove and fryer). More pub than bar, but a low quality in any regard. Tiniest bathrooms I've been to in a while. Everyone dropping 4 stars must be on crack or know the bartenders because when you travel around the country you'll see that being your favorite local bar or where everyone knows you doesn't make it good.

2 bouncers at the door were unnecessary and brutish, actually they were no larger than me, probably trained in some deadly martial art, not scaring anyone guys, everyone's trained now a days. 3 bouncers on a dead Saturday, odd. You should know they're there, but not everywhere checking up on you. If it wasn't for the only selling doubles, decent beer prices and selection and the outdoor patio garden area this place is a 1 star. Barely managing a 3 because drinkers are my people.</Text>

< pictures>

<Resp>None</Resp>< review>
Probably my favorite bar in the City since it's right by MUNI, never crowded enough that I don't have patio seating, and their beer selection is functionally as good as Toronado's. I was there last night and tried a coconut IPA, Big Leaf Maple, and an oatmeal porter.

One of the few places in the City that has Death n' Taxes on tap, so there's a solid option for all your dark beer lovers.

And all the beers are between $4 and $5, and during happy hour, it's all slightly discounted, so nice craft beers at rock bottom bar prices!

Props to the bouncer as well. I had left my ID at Burning Man, but I just explained it to him and he waved me through. #burnerproblems

Close enough to the Mission to stumble there for burritos or Indian food as well, so all your needs are met. And as Nique F. reminded me, Zeitgeist rolls out its own burgers and grilled cheese sammiches, so you can stay here for your vittles too.<//review>
